The thermostat system as a whole is a crucial part of the cooling system.

Just to recap for those not familiar with the type 1 cooling system:

The flaps direct airflow to the tops of each individual cylinder using the
Venturi Effect. Each vane and flap narrows the opening of the shroud to the
head, splits the air and blasts and directs it onto the tops of each
individual cylinder. So they serve two purposes, closed they heat up the
cylinder quickly to increase combustion efficiency and open greatly improve
cooling efficiency.

The bottom pieces have the same design principle and are indeed a piece of
the cooling system. They catch, speed up and hustle the hot air away from
the cylinder heads. If missing, the hot air tends linger, which isn't good.

Type 3 "cool tin" speeds up the hot air evacuation even more, catching hot
air from both sides of the head and directs it down vertically.

Once again, if they weren't needed, they wouldn't have put them in!

The only bad thing about a missing thermostat, flaps and rod: you have to
pull the motor to install them. Not fun if your motor runs fine, so it is
routinely avoided.

Jon Stiles
